Exploration of Diamond Prices

Author: Satakarni Bommuluri

Abstract

In this paper, I perform Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) on diamonds dataset to understand the important features that impact the prices of diamonds in crucial manner.

About the Dataset

The Diamonds dataset used in this EDA is part of the ggplot library. The dataset consists of a list of about 54000 diamonds. Each record comprise the price of a diamond and features of a diamond such as 4Cs: carat, cut, clarity, color, and volume related information. Below are the list of columns.

Univariate Analysis

The univariate analysis provides information about the distribution of individual variable for a given dataset.

Structure of dataset

The diamond dataset has 10 variables with almost 54000 records. Additionally it has three variables cut, color, and clarity that are factors with ordered levels.

Main feature(s) of interest in dataset

In general the important features of a diamond are 4 Cs : cut, clarity, color, and carat. Specifically in our dataset, the features cut, clarity, and color are discrete and carat is continuous. It would be interesting to notice price variance with 4Cs.

Other features of interest in the dataset

Besides 4Cs, I would like to analyze the price variance with depth, table, and volume.

Any new variables from existing variables in the dataset

Yes, volume is created from x,y, and z.

Commentary on unusual distributions, and data wraggling operations

Yes, the comments about distribution are mentioned below each plot in Section univariant plot section. The dataset is pretty tidy with few missing values for x,y, and z. During the analysis, we will ignore these missing values. During plot section, adjustments are made to zoom into certain part of data for more details.

ggplot(data = diamonds, aes(x = cut, y = price)) + 
    geom_boxplot() + 
    scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0,10000,1000)) +
    coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0,10000)) + 
    labs(x="Cut Grades", y = "Price($)", title = "Boxplot of Cut after removing outliers") +
    theme(axis.ticks = element_blank(), 
          panel.background = element_blank(), 
          panel.grid = element_blank(),
          axis.text.x = element_text(), 
          plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

The intuitive expectation would be increase in price with cut quality. However with our analysis the variance in price with cut is not giving a clear patter of ascending order. This might be due to other features influencing price along with cut. For instance high quality cut diamonds might be having lower carat in our dataset. Therefore, we will revisit cut variable in multivariant analysis to address these questions.

price vs.depth, table

As depth and table are continuous variables, I will begin with correlation test and continue my analysis with scatter plots against price, respectively.

The relation between depth and price is as follow:

## [1] -0.0106474

Hence it implies there is hardly any relation (positive or negative) between depth and price of diamond. If we depict a scatter plot on these variables, we should expect variance in price for set of constant values of depth.

The plot tells the same story as the correlation number calculated per Pearson method.

The relation between table and price is as follow:

## [1] 0.1271339

Here it implies there is an insignificant relation between table and price of diamond. If we depict a scatter plot on these two variables, we should a very slight variance in price for set of constant values of table.

In conclusion, the variables depth and table hardly have any correlation with price variable. We can drop these variables from further analysis.

price vs.volume

As volume is a continuous variable, I will determine its correlation with price followed by a scatter plot.

## [1] 0.9023845

It implies a strong positive relation between these two variables. We will expect a linear relation between volume and price.

As expected from correlation coefficient, there is a near linear relation between volume and price.

Multivariate Plots Section

The following multivariant plots are depicted. Each plot has a title referring with Figure number and description.

Multivariate Analysis

Relationships observed in this part of the investigation.

In this section, I will also discuss the features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at the above stated feature(s) of interest.

  1. Figure# 1 indicate price variance by carat for different qualities of diamond cut. It can be observed that there exists some evidence that price of the diamond increases with the quality of cut. However this relationship is not strong.

  2. Figure# 2 Figure# 1 indicate price variance by carat for different qualities of diamond clarity. In bi-variate analysis, i established that there is strong relationship between price and carat. The variable clarity added another strong dimension on top of carat to influence the price of a diamond. As it can observed, the prices of diamond reach increases (lm slope decreases) as the diamonds clarity increases for a given carat.

  3. The scatter plots Figure# 1 and Figure# 2 are colored based on the color of the diamond. I observed that quality of diamond color increases with carat! So I plotted Figure #3 to test out this hypothesis. The medians of the box plots indicate that quality of color and carat have a positive linear relationship.

  4. Figure #4 and Figure #5 are the price vs.density (carat/volume) scatter plots, while Figure #4 is faceted for different diamond cut. The density of diamond hardly varies. After recalling of high school basics and [Google search] (https://socratic.org/questions/why-is-density-constant), i realized the density of a substance (esp., solids) remains almost constant. Hence the plots are telling correct facts. Also an obvious observation is that high quality cut with lower density are priced higher than low quality cut with high density.

  5. Figure #5 depict scatter plot of carat vs. price for different colors of cut and faceted by clarity. From this plot it is observed that features carat and clariy should be considered to predict diamond prices.

Interesting or surprising interactions between features

For me Figure# 3 is interesting. The plot almost states that in order to improve the quality of color we have to increase the carat (weight) of diamond. So its not possible to have small diamonds with high quality of color? Figure# 4 and Figure# 5 were interesting until i recalled that density of a material remains almost constant!

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

The bi modal distribution of price histogram indicate two pricing segments of diamonds, from our dataset. The pricing segment breaks $1500.00, and that 37% are below $1500.00 and remaining 63% are prices above $1500.00.

## [1] "the mean carat for diamonds with price < $1500"
## [1] 0.3677041
## [1] "the mean carat for diamonds with price > $1500"
## [1] 1.051668

It can speculated that low carat diamond items like small ear rings and pendants are targeted for below $1500 market, while engagement rings that require on an average 1 carat are the market segments of above $1500.

Plot Two

Description Two

An understanding from this plot is that high grade color in diamonds is difficult with low carat diamonds. This is against to my intuition that low carat diamonds are usually colorless (high quality) and that impurity is easily possible for large diamonds. A meaningful causality is difficult to establish here. However it could be possible, at least in our dataset, that precautions are taken on large diamonds to keep their color grade quality as high.

Plot Three

Description Three

An important indication of this plot is that slope of linear model is increasing (meaning increase of price y-axis) with increase in quality of clarity. Hence in addition to carat, I will consider carat to predict the price of a diamond. Considering other features may over fit the prediction model.

Reflection

The exploration begun with understanding the dataset followed by univariate analysis, bivariate analysis and multivariate analysis. The area I struggled initially is to understand the domain knowledge of diamonds (4Cs, depth, table). The dataset helped me gain the domain knowledge. I will further this research to create a linear regression model to predict the price of a diamond.
